  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">DRC COVID-19 Global Appeal West Africa Region</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">DRC is present in &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.drc.ngo/where-we-work/west-africa&quot;&gt;6 countries&lt;/a&gt; in the West Africa Region and has implemented Covid-19 specific activities in all of these countries: &lt;i&gt; Burkina Faso, Central African Republic &amp; Niger &lt;/i&gt;.  


As of October 2020, &lt;b&gt; Basic Needs and Economic Recovery &lt;/b&gt; are the sectors that have had the most reach to the targeted communities we serve.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Having adapted its current operations with risk reduction measures to continue providing emergency humanitarian assistance, DRC in West and Central Africa is now adjusting to strengthen &lt;b&gt; Emergency Protection, Food Security, Distribution of non-food items, WASH and Shelter &lt;/b&gt; activities. This scaling up is coordinated with key actors in health and socio-economic responses and benefits from existing networks of community focal points, local teams and know-how acquired in the region focusing on access and resilience employing innovative approaches.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">&lt;b&gt; In Cameroon &lt;/b&gt;, DRC is purchasing WASH, PPE, and individual protection assistance kits for victims of protection incidents, commonly targeting children &amp; women. 


&lt;b&gt; In Niger &amp; Central African Republic &lt;/b&gt;, the focus is on people fleeing conflict who require Shelter and WASH assistance. 


&lt;b&gt; In Mali &lt;/b&gt;, certain needs such as health and hygiene needs have been addressed through individual protection assistance (IPA)and the provision of hand washing kits, soaps, gels and masks to IDPs in order to prevent spread of COVID-19.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">&lt;b&gt; The OECD DAC CRS Purpose Codes &lt;/b&gt; used to describe this activity refers to the amount of people reached, seen as a percentage of all single instances of beneficiaries reached. This means that it can include double counting, if single individuals have been counted multiple times for different sectors.</narrative>
  </description>
